stylometry: Risksimtable allows you to put in a range of input values; and essentially simulate for each value to help make your decision. In a simulation model this would be put in your changing cell (labeled accordingly depending on the "problem") and you put in the function "risksimtable" highlighting the possible quantities to use can range from 5 different values to "x" number, etc. After determining how many values you have and how many simulations it will run through - you press start simulation; the table this provides will show each value (that you put into risksimtable) and the results; allowing you to better make your decision. This is because rather than one value at a time, you can see each value and the results at one given time; essentially it helps your run time (you won't have to simulate the problem as much), etc. An example would be the Science Textbook Problem from chapter 11 (a group problem I worked on) - in this problem it gave possible quantities to try to figure ordering of more textbooks ( it was unique because in this problem we already had a starting point of 2000 books on hand); also the values to try were 6 values = 0, 1000, 2000, 4000, 6000, 8000. 0 being "do nothing" which essentially is an option that a business does not some times consider. I put these six values into my risksimtable function and it allowed me to see the results of each; and be one of the factors to consider when making a final decision.
